    "description": "Mowgli, the boy raised by wolves, grows up in the jungle.",
    "duration": "10",
    "pages": [
      [
        "Page 1",
        "Deep in the Indian jungle, Father Wolf prowled home one starry night. Near his cave he stopped, ears pricked. A tiny shape crawled through the tall grass — a human baby, plump and unafraid, with dark curls and bright brown eyes. The baby gripped Father Wolf's fur and laughed. 'A man-cub!' Father Wolf whispered in wonder. He carried the child gently home to his den, where his wife waited."
      ],
      [
        "Page 2",
        "Before Father Wolf could settle, a great voice roared outside. It was Shere Khan, the lame tiger with stripes like black fire. 'A man-cub ran into your cave,' he growled. 'Give him to me. He is mine.' Father Wolf's hackles rose. The cave was too narrow for the tiger to enter, and Shere Khan paced in fury, his heavy tail lashing the ferns."
      ],
      [
        "Page 3",
        "Then Mother Wolf stepped forward, her eyes burning green. The jungle called her Raksha, which means The Demon, for none could match her courage. 'The man-cub is mine!' she snarled. 'He shall run with my pack. Go, burnt one, before I teach you manners.' Shere Khan snorted, furious but beaten for now. He slunk away into the shadows, promising revenge one day soon."
      ],
      [
        "Page 4",
        "When the moon rose full, the wolves gathered at Council Rock. Akela, the great grey leader, looked down from a high stone. 'Who speaks for this man-cub?' he asked. By jungle law, two voices not of the pack must vouch for a strange cub. Silence fell. Then a deep, velvet voice rumbled from the darkness, and every wolf turned. It was Bagheera, the black panther, eyes gleaming like polished gold."
      ],
      [
        "Page 5",
        "'I speak for the man-cub,' Bagheera purred, 'and I offer a fat bull I have just killed.' Then old Baloo, the sleepy brown bear who taught the cubs the Law, shuffled forward. 'I too speak for him,' Baloo yawned. 'Let him run with the pack.' And so little Mowgli — for that was his name — was accepted. He tumbled among the wolf cubs, laughing at the stars."
      ],
      [
        "Page 6",
        "The years rolled by like slow, green rivers. Mowgli grew tall and brown, with tangled black hair and quick, clever hands. He ran on two legs when he pleased and on four when it was faster. He pulled thorns from the wolves' paws and knew every trail, every waterhole, every secret of the tall trees. The jungle was his home, and the wolves were his brothers and sisters."
      ],
      [
        "Page 7",
        "Baloo was strict. 'Say the hunting call of your people!' he would grumble, cuffing Mowgli gently when he forgot. Mowgli learned the words for bird and snake, for buffalo and bat. He learned the Master Words that kept a jungle creature safe: 'We be of one blood, ye and I.' Baloo grumbled and scolded, but his old heart swelled with pride at every lesson Mowgli remembered."
      ],
      [
        "Page 8",
        "Bagheera taught different lessons. The panther moved like flowing ink, silent and swift. 'Watch my shoulders, little brother,' Bagheera whispered. 'Step where I step.' Mowgli learned to climb, to swim, to freeze perfectly still. One evening, resting in a mango tree, Bagheera murmured, 'Remember, Mowgli — Shere Khan has not forgotten you. The day will come when he hunts you in earnest.' Mowgli only laughed, unafraid."
      ],
      [
        "Page 9",
        "One lazy afternoon, Mowgli was dozing when grey hands seized him. The Bandar-log — the foolish monkey people — snatched him up through the treetops, chattering and cackling. They carried him far away to a ruined palace tangled in vines. 'You shall be our king!' they screeched, dancing in circles around him. Mowgli's heart thumped, but he remembered Baloo's lesson and whispered a secret word to a passing kite."
      ],
      [
        "Page 10",
        "The kite carried the message to Bagheera and Baloo, who rushed to the ruins with Kaa, the wise old rock python. Kaa's shimmering coils stretched thirty feet long, and the monkeys feared him above all creatures. The three friends burst upon the palace, and the Bandar-log scattered in every direction. Bagheera swept Mowgli up in his strong paws. 'Little brother,' he sighed, 'never wander alone again.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 11",
        "More years passed, and Mowgli grew toward manhood. But trouble crept back like a shadow at dusk. Shere Khan had gathered young, hungry wolves to his side, whispering that a man-cub had no place in the pack. Old Akela was greying now, his bones weary. The council grew restless and divided. Bagheera listened, flicking his tail. One evening, he came to Mowgli with grave eyes and a warning on his tongue."
      ],
      [
        "Page 12",
        "'The pack is turning, little brother,' Bagheera said softly. 'Shere Khan waits for Akela to miss a single kill, and then the stripes will demand your life.' Mowgli sat very still. For the first time, he felt a strange hot sting behind his eyes. 'What shall I do?' he asked. Bagheera's golden gaze softened. 'Go down to the village of men. Bring back the Red Flower.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 13",
        "The Red Flower was fire — the one thing every jungle creature feared. Mowgli crept down the hills to a human village at twilight. He peered through an open doorway and saw a woman tending a clay pot of glowing coals. When she stepped away, Mowgli borrowed a single ember and carried it home in a hollow gourd, feeding it gently with dry twigs until it danced bright and fierce."
      ],
      [
        "Page 14",
        "That night at Council Rock, the wolves gathered in nervous silence. Shere Khan prowled among them, eyes like yellow lamps. 'Give me the man-cub!' he snarled. But Mowgli rose tall, holding a flaming branch high above his head. The wolves shrank back from the heat. Shere Khan himself flinched. 'This is the Red Flower,' Mowgli said, voice shaking with sorrow and fire. 'Stand back — all of you.'"
      ],
      [
        "Page 15",
        "Mowgli swept the burning branch toward Shere Khan's whiskers. The tiger yelped and fled into the night, tail between his legs. The faithless wolves scattered. Only Akela, Bagheera, and four loyal wolf brothers remained by Mowgli's side. Mowgli wept then — not from fear, but from a sadness he could not name. 'I do not understand my own heart,' he whispered. Bagheera nudged his cheek gently with a warm nose."
      ],
      [
        "Page 16",
        "But Shere Khan was not finished. He lurked in a narrow ravine, certain Mowgli would pass that way. Mowgli, though, had a plan. With his wolf brothers' help, he drove a great herd of buffalo — hooves thundering like drums — straight into the ravine from both ends. The tiger had nowhere to run. Mowgli stood on a high rock and watched the dust rise. The jungle's bully troubled them no more."
      ],
      [
        "Page 17",
        "Bagheera laid his head against Mowgli's shoulder one last time. 'You have done what no man-cub has done before,' he purred. 'But now you must go where you belong — among your own kind.' Mowgli's eyes filled. He hugged Baloo's shaggy neck, touched Akela's grey muzzle, and whispered farewell to every wolf brother. The jungle he loved would always be his, but the path before him led elsewhere."
      ],
      [
        "Page 18",
        "At sunrise, Mowgli walked slowly toward the distant village, carrying only a smooth walking stick and a gourd of embers. Birds called goodbye from the high branches. A panther's shadow slipped beside him for a little while, then melted into the green. Mowgli did not look back, though his heart was full. He would learn the ways of men now. And on quiet nights forever after, the jungle would whisper his name in the wind."
      ]
    ],
